text:
RT @JohnGHendy: What RBG's death means for the moment:

"Into that cauldron now goes a Supreme Court fight, with an outcome that could alter American society not only for the next four years, but for a generation to come." https://t.co/LYxWwWtyfW via @russellberman

name: TheAtlantic
TheAtlantic
text: RT @russellberman: Mitch McConnell announced within hours of Antonin Scalia's death in 2016 that any replacement nominated by President Obama would not get a Senate vote. Less than 2 hours after Ginsburg's death, he says that Trump's nominee will: https://t.co/neABdxh8tC

name: TheAtlantic
text: The fandom that embraced Ruth Bader Ginsburg reveled in playful kitsch. But, @megangarber writes, it was never frivolous. https://t.co/ueSpMnBhF5

name: TheAtlantic
text: “If an opening comes in the last year of President Trump’s term and the primary process is started, we’ll wait for the next election,” South Carolina Senator Lindsey Graham said during an interview with @jeffreygoldberg in 2018. https://t.co/OcIPa9qN8B

name: TheAtlantic
text: RT @AdrienneLaF: I always found the cult of RBG to be  vaguely unsettling, weirdly infantilizing, and too cute. But @megangarber persuasively makes the case that informality can be a “soaring and searing and eloquent” form of respect. Very much worth reading: https://t.co/xNVlJyCIvx

name: TheAtlantic
text: Ruth Bader Ginsburg was “far more than the gangsta-feminist we’ve turned her into,” @dahlialithwick argued in 2019. She was “a bit of a dork and a lot of a grind and a perfectionist and an idealist.” https://t.co/H9svWyxpL2
